<div class="section">

<h2>Project Overview</h2>

<p>
This project presents a fluid-mechanical dissection and qualitative analysis of the
<strong>Stihl BR 700 backpack leaf blower</strong>, a high-performance handheld air-moving device.
The objective was to physically dismantle the system, document its internal components,
and analyze how its geometry and configuration govern airflow generation, acceleration,
and discharge.
</p>

<p>
The dissection was performed to reinforce core concepts from fluid mechanics, including
conservation laws, internal flow behavior, turbomachinery fundamentals, and loss mechanisms
in real-world devices.
</p>

</div>


<div class="section">

<h2>Device Selection and Relevance to Fluid Mechanics</h2>

<p>
The Stihl BR 700 was selected because it functions as a compact centrifugal flow machine,
combining rotating machinery, confined internal flow passages, and high-Reynolds-number
airflow. The device provides a clear physical example of how mechanical energy is transferred
to a fluid to produce useful momentum and pressure rise.
</p>

<p>
Key fluid-mechanical phenomena exhibited by the device include:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>Energy transfer from a rotating impeller to airflow</li>
  <li>Radial-to-axial flow redirection</li>
  <li>Internal losses due to friction and turbulence</li>
  <li>Jet formation at the discharge nozzle</li>
</ul>

</div>


<div class="section">

<h2>Mechanical Dissection Procedure</h2>

<p>
The leaf blower was fully dismantled using standard hand tools, following safe mechanical
disassembly practices. Components were removed in a systematic sequence to preserve
structural integrity and allow clear observation of internal flow features.
</p>

<p>
Throughout the process, particular attention was paid to components that directly influence
fluid motion, including the intake housing, centrifugal fan, volute casing, and outlet ducting.
</p>

</div>


<div class="section">

