</p>

</div>


<div class="section">

<h2>Identification of Key Flow Components</h2>

<p>
The primary flow-influencing components identified during the dissection include:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Inlet Section:</strong> Draws ambient air into the blower with minimal pressure loss</li>
  <li><strong>Centrifugal Impeller:</strong> Transfers mechanical energy to the air, increasing velocity and pressure</li>
  <li><strong>Volute Housing:</strong> Converts kinetic energy into static pressure while guiding flow circumferentially</li>
  <li><strong>Outlet Ducting and Nozzle:</strong> Accelerates and directs airflow into a high-speed jet</li>
</ul>

<p>
The geometry of the impeller blades and volute directly controls flow acceleration,
pressure rise, and efficiency.
</p>

</div>


<div class="section">

<h2>Flow Pathway Analysis</h2>

<p>
Air enters axially through the intake and is redirected radially outward by the rotating
impeller. As the air moves through the volute, its velocity is partially converted into
pressure before being redirected toward the outlet duct.
</p>

<p>
Potential regions of flow separation and recirculation were observed near sharp turns
and sudden cross-sectional changes, particularly within the volute and outlet transition.
These regions contribute to aerodynamic losses and reduced efficiency.
</p>

</div>


<div class="section">

<h2>Application of Fluid Mechanical Principles</h2>

<p>
The blower operation can be explained using fundamental conservation principles:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Conservation of Mass:</strong> Continuity applies throughout the internal flow passages</li>
  <li><strong>Conservation of Momentum:</strong> The impeller imparts momentum to the air, generating thrust</li>
  <li><strong>Conservation of Energy:</strong> Mechanical shaft work is converted into fluid kinetic and pressure energy</li>
</ul>

<p>
The airflow operates at high Reynolds numbers, indicating fully turbulent internal flow.
Losses due to boundary layers, turbulence, and secondary flows play a significant role
in overall performance.
</p>

</div>


<div class="section">

<h2>Losses and Efficiency Considerations</h2>

<p>
Major sources of loss identified include:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>Frictional losses along internal walls</li>
  <li>Turbulent dissipation within the volute</li>
  <li>Flow separation at sharp geometric transitions</li>
</ul>

<p>
These losses reduce the fraction of mechanical energy converted into useful airflow.
Design features such as smooth curvature and gradual area changes are critical for
maintaining efficiency.
</p>

</div>


<div class="section">

<h2>Safety and Procedural Considerations</h2>

<p>
All disassembly steps were conducted with the device powered off, cooled, and free of fuel.
Personal protective equipment was used to mitigate risks associated with sharp edges and
stored mechanical energy.
</p>

</div>


<div class="section">

<h2>Reflection on Fluid Mechanical Phenomena</h2>

<p>
This dissection reinforced the relationship between mechanical design and fluid behavior.
Observing internal components firsthand provided clarity on how theoretical concepts
translate into practical engineering solutions.
</p>

<p>
The project highlighted discrepancies between idealized flow assumptions and real-world
performance, particularly regarding losses and non-uniform flow structures.
</p>

</div>


<div class="section">

<h2>Conclusion</h2>

<p>
The fluid mechanical dissection of the Stihl BR 700 demonstrated how centrifugal machinery,
internal flow passages, and geometric design collectively govern airflow generation.
This project strengthened practical understanding of turbomachinery and internal flow
mechanics beyond what is achievable through theory alone.
</p>

</div>
